1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:46,800
Over here.

3
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:52,000
Steve Martin's the name.

4
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:10,200
It grew.

5
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Thank you. Tell you what I'll do.

6
00:02:15,100 --> 00:02:17,300
You call out a tune, and I'll play it.

7
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:19,300
<i>Stay in Your Own Backyard.</i>

8
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:21,300
Too dirty back there.

9
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:26,500
- Any other tune?
- <i>Banks of the Wabash.</i>

10
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:30,100
<i>Banks of the Wabash.</i> All right.
Now I'll tell you what I'll do.

11
00:02:30,100 --> 00:02:33,200
I'll play it if you folks will sing it. Right?

12
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:35,900
The key of C, Professor.

13
00:02:47,800 --> 00:02:49,400
So you won't sing?

14
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:52,600
Am I asking you to do me a favor?
I'm doing you a favor.

15
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:54,100
When you sing, what happens?

16
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:57,800
Your lungs get full of oxygen.
It puts roses on your cheeks.

17
00:02:58,100 --> 00:03:01,300
As a matter of fact, you either sing out,
or you get out.

18
00:03:02,100 --> 00:03:05,500
Now that we understand each other,
let's go, Professor.

19
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:19,400
<i>The breath of new-mown hay</i>

20
00:03:20,100 --> 00:03:22,700
<i>Through the sycamores</i>

21
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:27,100
<i>the candle lights are gleaming</i>

22
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:32,400
<i>on the banks of the Wabash, far away</i>

23
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:42,300
Fine. Stand up and let the folks see you.

24
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:45,200
Don't be bashful. Come on, stand right up.

25
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:47,500
Come on, folks, let's make him stand up.

26
00:03:50,500 --> 00:03:52,700
Attaboy! Let's have it again.

27
00:03:52,700 --> 00:03:54,700
Give that boy a spotlight!

28
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,400
Professor, let's have the chorus again.

29
00:04:03,900 --> 00:04:07,200
<i>Oh, the moonlight's fair tonight</i>

30
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:10,500
<i>along the Wabash</i>

31
00:04:10,900 --> 00:04:14,100
<i>From the fields there comes the breath</i>

32
00:04:14,100 --> 00:04:17,700
<i>of new-mown hay</i>

33
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:20,100
<i>Through the sycamores</i>

34
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:24,300
<i>the candle lights are gleaming</i>

35
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:29,700
<i>on the banks of the Wabash</i>

36
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:35,300
<i>far away</i>

37
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:47,000
- What's your name?
- Asa Yoelson.

38
00:04:47,500 --> 00:04:49,200
Are you in show business?

39
00:04:50,100 --> 00:04:51,500
No, sir, I'm not.

40
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:53,800
Where'd you learn to sing like that?

41
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:56,100
I sing with my father at the synagogue.

42
00:04:56,300 --> 00:04:58,300
- Where?
- At the...

43
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:00,600
The synagogue!

44
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:04,300
Wait a minute!

45
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:06,600
Sonny, wait a minute!

46
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:29,900
Answer me, Asa.
Where were you all that time?

47
00:06:30,400 --> 00:06:33,300
You came like someone
who is running a race.

48
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:36,100
It's not good to run a race with God, Asa.

49
00:06:36,100 --> 00:06:37,800
Where were you, Asa?

50
00:06:38,100 --> 00:06:40,800
I was... singing.

51
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
You mean you stayed home?

52
00:06:43,300 --> 00:06:46,200
- Practicing, is that what you mean?
- No.

53
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:49,500
Then where were you singing?
Stop cracking your knuckles.

54
00:06:49,500 --> 00:06:51,300
In the street, maybe?

55
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:53,400
That's not exactly where I was singing.

56
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:55,800
Singing prayers in the street.

57
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,500
- No, not exactly.
- Exactly?

58
00:06:58,500 --> 00:07:01,000
You must have been exactly somewhere...

59
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,100
singing exactly something...

60
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:06,100
- and for some exact reason.
- Yes, Papa.

61
00:07:14,300 --> 00:07:17,800
My name is Martin.
I'd like to talk to you for a minute.

62
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:20,200
Hello, Asa.

63
00:07:20,900 --> 00:07:23,000
You're Cantor Yoelson. I'm Steve Martin.

64
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,300
- How do you do?
- I'm glad to know you.

65
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:27,000
Your son has a real voice.

66
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:30,000
You were at the synagogue today
for the service?

67
00:07:29,900 --> 00:07:33,700
Me? No. I just went by there to find out
where you lived.

68
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:36,000
Then where did you hear my son sing?

69
00:07:35,900 --> 00:07:37,800
- At Kernan's.
- Kernan's?

70
00:07:37,800 --> 00:07:40,600
Yeah. The burlesque house
a few blocks from here.

71
00:07:40,600 --> 00:07:42,500
The burlesque theater?

72
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:46,200
- Don't you ever go there?
- No, I do not.

73
00:07:46,700 --> 00:07:49,200
That boy's got a future in show business.

74
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:51,800
I've looked for something like him
for a long time.

75
00:07:51,800 --> 00:07:53,900
I'd like to make him a regular part of the act.

76
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:55,300
You've nothing to worry about.

77
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:58,500
I'm booked solid for the season.
I move on to Baltimore tonight.

78
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,400
- Baltimore.
- I know he's pretty young...

79
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:03,900
but when a boy's got a voice like that,
he ought to let people hear it.

80
00:08:03,800 --> 00:08:06,600
You're right, Mr. Martin. Asa will sing.

81
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:09,500
But where his people have always sung.

82
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:11,100
I know how you feel.

83
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:16,000
It's a beautiful thing to sing in church,
but there's a lot to say for the theater, too.

84
00:08:15,900 --> 00:08:18,200
If you're worried
about my taking care of him...

85
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:20,000
Excuse me, Mr. Martin.

86
00:08:20,100 --> 00:08:22,800
I think I know what's best for my son.

87
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:29,000
I was afraid that's how you'd feel about it.

88
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:30,700
Sorry, Asa.

89
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:34,000
- Good night.
- Good night.

90
00:08:41,600 --> 00:08:45,400
I want your promise
that you'll never go to that place again.

91
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:52,500
I can't.

92
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:56,500
- I can't promise.
- Go to your room.

93
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,700
Ann, go downstairs and get a ladder.
Put it here.

94
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:28,900
- Why?
- Hurry up. Get the ladder.

95
00:10:07,400 --> 00:10:11,400
What'd you bring me here for?
Why don't you let me find Steve Martin?

96
00:10:11,300 --> 00:10:13,700
What kind of a car was that
you jumped out of?

97
00:10:13,700 --> 00:10:16,300
A cattle car.
What difference does that make?

98
00:10:16,300 --> 00:10:19,000
All the difference in the world, my boy.

99
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,200
- Here's another one, Father.
- Let me go.

100
00:10:21,100 --> 00:10:24,000
Yes, let him go, Riley. Don't mind him.

101
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,600
He just thinks he has to behave
like a policeman.

102
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:28,300
I don't think he understands boys.

103
00:10:28,300 --> 00:10:30,900
No? I've only got seven of them myself.

104
00:10:30,900 --> 00:10:32,600
That's just what I mean.

105
00:10:32,600 --> 00:10:35,300
Now, suppose you tell me about yourself.

106
00:10:36,800 --> 00:10:38,600
Where are you from?

107
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:41,400
- Where was he picked up?
- In the freight yard.

108
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:44,300
He came in on a cattle car. Can't you tell?

109
00:10:45,700 --> 00:10:49,000
If you knew about freight trains,
you'd never pick a cattle car.

110
00:10:48,800 --> 00:10:51,800
- I had to get here.
- To Baltimore? Why?

111
00:10:52,700 --> 00:10:55,200
- He's got a job here.
- What kind of job?

112
00:10:55,100 --> 00:10:57,800
- Singing.
- Singing? Where?

113
00:10:57,800 --> 00:11:01,100
In a show with Steve Martin.
He's in Baltimore right now.

114
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:04,100
What about your family?
Do they know about this?

115
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:05,900
I see.

116
00:11:06,600 --> 00:11:10,400
Before we do anything else,
I think you'd better have a hot bath.

117
00:11:10,200 --> 00:11:12,800
- And something to eat, John.
- Come on, my boy.

118
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:14,800
Why don't you find Steve Martin
and ask him?

119
00:11:14,700 --> 00:11:16,600
That's just what I'll do.

120
00:11:16,600 --> 00:11:20,400
Since it's singing he's interested in,
why not let him sing?

121
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:22,300
Sing?

122
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:46,800
Tell me a little more about your work
in the theater, Mr. Martin.

123
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:49,200
I've told you about all there is.

124
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:51,600
Pardon me, Father. I don't get it.

125
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:54,700
Why would you be bringing me here,
asking me all these questions?

126
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:59,400
- Is there something you want me to do?
- I'll come to the point in a little while.

127
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,900
- Cantor Yoelson? I'm Father McGee.
- How do you do?

128
00:12:12,900 --> 00:12:14,300
Mrs. Yoelson.

129
00:12:15,100 --> 00:12:17,000
Hello, glad to see you again.

130
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,900
- You know Mr. Martin?
- We know him.

131
00:12:19,900 --> 00:12:22,300
- Is our boy here?
- The description is like Asa.

132
00:12:22,300 --> 00:12:24,900
I have a very strong feeling that...

133
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:29,800
So have I.

134
00:12:54,200 --> 00:12:56,400
Singing without his cap on.

135
00:12:57,300 --> 00:13:01,100
It's not so much what's on the head
as what's in the heart...

136
00:13:00,900 --> 00:13:02,200
is it, Cantor?

137
00:13:29,800 --> 00:13:33,200
Hello, Mama. Hello, Papa.
Beautiful song, wasn't it?

138
00:13:36,800 --> 00:13:39,100
Get ready, Asa. We're going home.

139
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:41,600
I'll do it again, Papa. I'll run away.

140
00:13:41,600 --> 00:13:44,500
- I'll find Mr. Martin someplace.
- Now wait, Asa.

141
00:13:44,500 --> 00:13:48,100
I wouldn't have you in the act
if I didn't have your father's consent.

142
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:51,200
Then I'll get in another act.
I'll keep running away.

143
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:54,200
- What are we going to do with him?
- We'll decide that at home.

144
00:13:54,100 --> 00:13:56,600
Maybe we should decide now, Papa.

145
00:13:56,600 --> 00:13:58,900
You said you would take
very good care of our boy?

146
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:02,600
- You would consider this foolishness?
- I'm only asking, Papa.

147
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:05,700
If Asa is going to keep running away,
I have a right to ask.

148
00:14:05,700 --> 00:14:09,100
I made inquiries about Mr. Martin.
He's a man who can be trusted.

149
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:13,100
I'm sorry I started all this trouble
and I wouldn't have more to do with it...

150
00:14:12,900 --> 00:14:15,200
but considering his feelings
about show business...

151
00:14:15,100 --> 00:14:16,300
Show business!

152
00:14:16,300 --> 00:14:19,300
Tell me, Mr. Martin,
exactly what would Asa do?

153
00:14:19,300 --> 00:14:21,400
The same as I did at Kernan's, Mama.

154
00:14:21,400 --> 00:14:24,100
- Isn't that what you mean, Mr. Martin?
- Yes.

155
00:14:24,100 --> 00:14:27,100
Mr. Martin's onstage asking everybody
to sing, but nobody does...

156
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,100
'cause they're waiting
for someone else to begin.

157
00:14:29,100 --> 00:14:31,500
I'm up in the balcony, and Mr. Martin says:

158
00:14:31,500 --> 00:14:33,300
"Come on, folks! Join in the chorus!"

159
00:14:33,300 --> 00:14:35,700
"Don't be bashful. All together now."

160
00:14:35,700 --> 00:14:38,800
All of a sudden,
I stand up in the balcony and start singing.

161
00:14:38,600 --> 00:14:41,200
I'm dumbfounded at the kid's voice,
and I say:

162
00:14:41,200 --> 00:14:42,900
"Give that boy a spotlight!"

163
00:14:42,900 --> 00:14:43,400
"Give that boy a spotlight!"

164
00:14:43,900 --> 00:14:45,700
<i>I love you</i>

165
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:51,600
<i>as I've never loved before</i>

166
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:55,200
<i>Since first I met you</i>

167
00:14:55,200 --> 00:14:59,800
<i>on the village green</i>

168
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:03,300
<i>Come to me</i>

169
00:15:03,300 --> 00:15:07,300
<i>or my dream of love</i>

170
00:15:07,900 --> 00:15:11,000
<i>is over</i>

171
00:15:11,800 --> 00:15:16,700
<i>I love you as I loved you</i>

172
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:21,700
<i>when you were sweet</i>

173
00:15:22,300 --> 00:15:27,300
<i>when you were sweet</i>

174
00:15:27,700 --> 00:15:32,600
<i>sixteen</i>

175
00:15:43,400 --> 00:15:47,200
"Next week, Philadelphia, then Pittsburgh.

176
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:51,900
"Feeling fine.
Your loving son, Asa Yoelson."

177
00:15:52,300 --> 00:15:54,200
He's feeling fine.

178
00:15:55,400 --> 00:15:57,900
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh.

179
00:15:58,500 --> 00:16:00,900
Washington was too small for Asa.

180
00:16:05,300 --> 00:16:09,000
<i>- "Indianapolis."</i>
<i>- Indians! He'll come home scalped yet.</i>

181
00:16:11,100 --> 00:16:12,500
<i>"Kickabock."</i>

182
00:16:12,500 --> 00:16:15,900
<i>- Is this in the United States, Papa?</i>
<i>- Don't be foolish!</i>

183
00:16:20,700 --> 00:16:23,900
<i>- No. That's pronounced Di-bi-kah.</i>
<i>- Dubuque!</i>

184
00:16:23,900 --> 00:16:26,900
<i>Anyway, in Dubuque, he sang two encores.</i>

185
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:33,700
Now spell "tedious."

186
00:16:34,600 --> 00:16:37,900
T-E-D-O...

187
00:16:37,900 --> 00:16:41,000
Wait a minute. That's wrong.
Try again. "Tedious."

188
00:16:40,900 --> 00:16:44,100
You wouldn't know to spell it
if you didn't have that book.

189
00:16:44,100 --> 00:16:46,000
I'm not learning. I'm teaching.

190
00:16:47,500 --> 00:16:50,700
<i>By the light</i>

191
00:16:50,700 --> 00:16:55,200
<i>of the silvery moon, moon</i>

192
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:59,300
<i>I want to spoon</i>

193
00:16:59,300 --> 00:17:04,800
<i>to my honey I'll croon love's tune</i>

194
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:08,000
<i>Honey moon</i>

195
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:12,400
<i>keep a-shinin' in June</i>

196
00:17:12,300 --> 00:17:18,300
<i>Your silv'ry beams will bring love dreams</i>

197
00:17:18,700 --> 00:17:23,100
<i>We'll be cuddling soon</i>

198
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:27,400
<i>by the silvery moon</i>

199
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:45,500
Just a minute.

200
00:17:45,600 --> 00:17:47,900
How come suddenly
in the middle of the song...

201
00:17:47,900 --> 00:17:49,300
you put in a "moo-moo"?

202
00:17:49,300 --> 00:17:52,000
I thought it would be a little better that way.

203
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:53,800
You thought it would be a little better?

204
00:17:53,800 --> 00:17:56,600
If the guy who wrote the song
wanted to say "moo-moo"...

205
00:17:56,500 --> 00:17:57,800
he'd write it that way.

206
00:17:57,800 --> 00:18:01,000
I just get tired of singing it
the same way every time.

207
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:04,900
- So you thought up "moo-moo"?
- I didn't think it. It just came out.

208
00:18:05,500 --> 00:18:07,400
It just came out?

209
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:09,000
Don't let it come out!

210
00:18:09,100 --> 00:18:10,800
Sing that song just like it's written...

211
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:13,600
and I don't want to hear
no more "moo-moos."

212
00:18:13,600 --> 00:18:16,000
- Yes, sir.
- How do you like that?

213
00:18:15,900 --> 00:18:18,300
He gets tired singing it the same way...

214
00:18:18,300 --> 00:18:21,100
so he puts in "moo-moo."

215
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:24,600
As if that makes any difference.
And another thing...

216
00:18:24,800 --> 00:18:28,900
you're singing it a little faster every night.
Is that because you're tired, too?

217
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:31,700
No. That's because you're playing it
too slow.

218
00:18:32,500 --> 00:18:34,300
I'm playing it slow?

219
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:36,200
Excuse me.

220
00:18:36,200 --> 00:18:40,400
I've only been in this business for 30 years,
making a very nice living.

221
00:18:40,300 --> 00:18:43,000
But maybe an old trouper like you
ought to come on stage...

222
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:46,900
I thought of that.
I could sing much better on the stage.

223
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:48,300
You don't tell me.

224
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:51,700
Then I can sing right to them
instead of the backs of their heads...

225
00:18:51,600 --> 00:18:54,300
- and I could see how their faces look.
- The faces?

226
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:56,900
Unless you can see the people's faces,
it's no good at all.

227
00:18:56,900 --> 00:19:00,000
You don't say. And tell me, Mr. Yoelson...

228
00:19:00,600 --> 00:19:03,700
with that spotlight
shining right in your eyes...

229
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:06,000
- how are you gonna see faces?
- That's easy.

230
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:10,800
If you turn up all the lights in the theater,
then they can see me, and I can see them.

231
00:19:12,600 --> 00:19:15,100
Asa in long pants.

232
00:19:21,300 --> 00:19:25,900
<i>Goodbye, my bluebell</i>

233
00:19:25,800 --> 00:19:30,400
<i>farewell to you</i>

234
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:33,100
<i>One last fond look</i>

235
00:19:33,100 --> 00:19:38,100
<i>into your eyes so blue</i>

236
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:43,500
<i>'Mid campfires gleaming</i>

237
00:19:43,500 --> 00:19:48,500
<i>'mid shot and shell</i>

238
00:19:56,800 --> 00:19:58,400
<i>Goodbye</i>

239
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:37,800
- You don't wanna be in the act anymore?
- No, Steve.

240
00:20:38,200 --> 00:20:39,500
I'm going home.

241
00:20:39,800 --> 00:20:42,700
Don't be silly.
Your voice is changing, that's all.

242
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:45,400
In a couple of years,
you'll get it back, better than ever.

243
00:20:45,300 --> 00:20:48,800
And listen, the way
you pulled that whistle out of the hat...

244
00:20:48,800 --> 00:20:51,300
that's showmanship.
Didn't you hear them applaud?

245
00:20:51,300 --> 00:20:53,900
- But it isn't the same.
- What isn't the same?

246
00:20:53,800 --> 00:20:55,900
The act's just as good as it was before.

247
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,000
When you whistle,
their faces don't look the same.

248
00:20:59,700 --> 00:21:02,900
Faces again. This kid'll drive me crazy.

249
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:07,400
Listen, I didn't say you're gonna whistle
the rest of your life.

250
00:21:07,700 --> 00:21:11,100
Just for a while.
Look, know what we're gonna do?

251
00:21:11,400 --> 00:21:13,500
We're gonna work up
some whistling routines...

252
00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:16,300
and you're gonna
work on the stage with me.

253
00:21:16,300 --> 00:21:17,700
What do you think of that?

254
00:21:17,700 --> 00:21:20,900
And do you know something else?
Then you're gonna get billing.

255
00:21:20,900 --> 00:21:21,900
Yes, sir!

256
00:21:21,900 --> 00:21:26,300
"Meet that scintillating team of artists:
Steve Martin and Asa Yoelson."

257
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:30,400
Asa Yoelson.

258
00:21:33,400 --> 00:21:37,400
"Now I whistle in the act.
Everyone seems to like it.

259
00:21:37,500 --> 00:21:39,400
"Your loving son..."

260
00:21:43,300 --> 00:21:46,700
- Papa, Asa isn't Asa anymore!
- What?

261
00:21:57,500 --> 00:21:59,900
<i>In Reno, Papa, he's picking up time.</i>

262
00:21:59,900 --> 00:22:02,800
<i>Is time something you can pick up?</i>
<i>This is crazy.</i>

263
00:22:05,700 --> 00:22:08,600
<i>This town they liked so much,</i>
<i>they named it twice.</i>

264
00:22:12,300 --> 00:22:16,400
<i>He says he can't come home this summer.</i>
<i>Maybe next spring.</i>

265
00:22:36,400 --> 00:22:38,900
<i>Since first I met you</i>

266
00:22:39,900 --> 00:22:43,300
<i>on the village green</i>

267
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:54,200
- Listen.
- What's the matter?

268
00:22:54,300 --> 00:22:55,800
<i>Come to me</i>

269
00:22:56,300 --> 00:22:59,300
<i>for my dream of love</i>

270
00:22:59,300 --> 00:23:02,100
<i>is all</i>

271
00:23:02,700 --> 00:23:07,400
<i>I love you as I loved you</i>

272
00:23:08,100 --> 00:23:11,500
<i>When you were sweet</i>

273
00:23:12,100 --> 00:23:17,300
<i>When you were sweet</i>

274
00:23:18,200 --> 00:23:22,000
<i>sixteen</i>

275
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:25,800
What do you think?

276
00:23:25,900 --> 00:23:28,500
Are we going into this again
in the middle of the night?

277
00:23:28,500 --> 00:23:32,100
- It's getting better every time.
- All right, it's getting better.

278
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,800
I told you, let it alone. Give yourself time.

279
00:23:34,800 --> 00:23:38,200
- Go away. Go sing in the bathroom.
- Why not let me try?

280
00:23:38,100 --> 00:23:40,000
You mean all of a sudden,
tomorrow maybe...

281
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:42,900
- in the middle of the act, you wanna sing?
- Why not?

282
00:23:42,800 --> 00:23:44,700
- You're daffy.
- Why?

283
00:23:45,300 --> 00:23:47,600
We're changing no act
in the middle of the season...

284
00:23:47,600 --> 00:23:49,100
and fall flat on our face.

285
00:23:49,100 --> 00:23:50,300
We're gonna do like I said.

286
00:23:50,300 --> 00:23:53,200
We're gonna knock off a month next spring.

287
00:23:53,200 --> 00:23:55,800
Won't take no. Never stops.

288
00:23:56,400 --> 00:23:58,500
This guy'll drive me crazy.

289
00:23:59,900 --> 00:24:03,600
<i>He's getting close to home.</i>
<i>We'll see him soon, Papa.</i>

290
00:24:03,900 --> 00:24:06,700
- Hello, Pop. How's tricks?
- Letter for you.

291
00:24:08,900 --> 00:24:10,700
Mama. Always on time.

292
00:24:11,100 --> 00:24:13,500
- Overture!
- Come on, Al.

293
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:19,800
Mama's excited.
Three more weeks, and we go home.

294
00:24:19,800 --> 00:24:22,400
- I could use a nice month's rest.
- Not a month.

295
00:24:22,300 --> 00:24:24,900
I don't want to stay home that long.
Just a few days.

296
00:24:24,800 --> 00:24:27,300
We have to work on the new act
and the stuff I'll sing.

297
00:24:27,300 --> 00:24:30,700
I know. There'll be time.
Take it easy. Just relax.

298
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:38,000
- Stop arguing.
- Just humming a little.

299
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,300
When you sing,
it means you're getting ideas.

300
00:24:40,300 --> 00:24:41,900
I was thinking of something.

301
00:24:41,900 --> 00:24:44,400
In Nashville and Charleston,
the last two dates...

302
00:24:44,300 --> 00:24:46,700
why can't I sing just one chorus
of <i>Sweet Sixteen?</i>

303
00:24:46,700 --> 00:24:48,300
- No.
- Just to see how it sounds.

304
00:24:48,300 --> 00:24:50,500
Won't matter if I flop.

305
00:24:50,700 --> 00:24:53,600
Just in Charleston, then.
Let me sing it once the last night.

306
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:56,000
That little Connolly kid
is awful sweet on you.

307
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:58,600
Give her a tumble
and get your mind on something else.

308
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:00,700
- Don't you think of girls?
- I haven't got time.

309
00:25:00,700 --> 00:25:03,300
All I'm asking is just one chance. That's all...

310
00:25:03,300 --> 00:25:04,500
Stop arguing!

311
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:08,500
I bet the Kentucky Derby winner.

312
00:25:08,500 --> 00:25:10,500
I win a snootful!

313
00:25:10,500 --> 00:25:12,700
A snootful is right. You better get ready.

314
00:25:12,700 --> 00:25:15,000
I got ready, boy, and I win!

315
00:25:14,900 --> 00:25:17,300
Get yourself together.
You're on in a little while.

316
00:25:17,300 --> 00:25:20,900
- I'll be there with flying colors.
- He can't go on like that.

317
00:25:20,900 --> 00:25:23,900
We better tell Jonesy to skip the act,
and get ready ourselves.

318
00:25:23,800 --> 00:25:25,100
You get made up.

319
00:25:25,200 --> 00:25:29,300
- I gotta try and pull this guy together.
- All right, but hurry up.

320
00:25:30,800 --> 00:25:34,800
There's a big derby crowd out there tonight.
The house is packed. You gotta go on.

321
00:25:36,900 --> 00:25:39,000
I'm raring to go.

322
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:49,600
Oscar Hammerstein and Lew Dockstader!
What are they doing here?

323
00:26:49,600 --> 00:26:51,300
Down for the races.

324
00:26:51,300 --> 00:26:54,200
Why did you drag me here
when we could've been playing poker?

325
00:26:54,200 --> 00:26:57,800
Anything on a stage, Oscar, and I love it.
I see them all.

326
00:26:59,500 --> 00:27:01,700
- You're on, Mr. Baron.
- Ready.

327
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:52,700
Anytime you're ready to go, Lew.

328
00:28:00,600 --> 00:28:03,000
Tom, you're all right? Where's Al?

329
00:28:03,400 --> 00:28:06,400
He was with you, wasn't he?
Where did he go?

330
00:28:06,800 --> 00:28:08,200
All right, Tom.

331
00:28:10,600 --> 00:28:13,200
Tom, come on, get out there. Hurry up!

332
00:28:19,300 --> 00:28:22,400
<i>There's a little bunch of sweetness</i>

333
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:25,100
<i>that I long to call my bride</i>

334
00:28:25,300 --> 00:28:28,400
<i>And believe me, I'm not happy</i>

335
00:28:28,700 --> 00:28:30,400
<i>But, baby</i>

336
00:28:30,900 --> 00:28:33,700
Funny thing,
I've sung this song a thousand times...

337
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,600
Why I forgot it tonight, I don't know.

338
00:28:39,300 --> 00:28:41,700
<i>You'll hear me call her name</i>

339
00:28:41,700 --> 00:28:43,100
I got it now.

340
00:28:44,100 --> 00:28:49,100
<i>Rosie, you are my posie</i>

341
00:28:49,900 --> 00:28:54,800
<i>You are my heart's bouquet</i>

342
00:28:55,600 --> 00:29:00,400
<i>Come out here in the moonlight</i>

343
00:29:00,200 --> 00:29:05,200
<i>There's something sweet love, I want to say</i>

344
00:29:07,300 --> 00:29:11,600
<i>Your honey boy, I'm waiting</i>

345
00:29:12,800 --> 00:29:17,800
<i>Those ruby lips to greet</i>

346
00:29:18,100 --> 00:29:23,100
<i>Don't be so aggravating</i>

347
00:29:23,200 --> 00:29:27,200
Baron's developed a very nice style.
Very nice.

348
00:29:29,700 --> 00:29:31,800
<i>Rosie</i>

349
00:29:32,600 --> 00:29:35,300
<i>you are my posie</i>

350
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:40,600
<i>You are my heart's bouquet</i>

351
00:29:42,100 --> 00:29:46,900
<i>Come out here in the moonlight</i>

352
00:29:46,700 --> 00:29:49,400
<i>there's something sweet love</i>

353
00:29:49,800 --> 00:29:54,500
<i>I'm gonna sing about my baby, your honey</i>

354
00:29:55,100 --> 00:29:58,000
<i>Your boy, I'm waiting</i>

355
00:29:58,400 --> 00:30:03,500
<i>Those ruby, those lips to greet</i>

356
00:30:03,400 --> 00:30:08,000
<i>Don't be so aggravating</i>

357
00:30:07,900 --> 00:30:10,800
<i>My blushin' Rosie</i>

358
00:30:10,700 --> 00:30:14,400
<i>my posie sweet!</i>

359
00:30:19,600 --> 00:30:21,000
Did you hear that finish?

360
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:23,100
Come on, Tom. Get out there!

361
00:30:23,100 --> 00:30:24,700
I don't know any more of Tom's songs.

362
00:30:24,700 --> 00:30:27,900
Take a bow and collapse.
Get yourself off! Go on!

363
00:30:37,400 --> 00:30:39,300
- What's the matter?
- He's sick.

364
00:30:39,300 --> 00:30:41,100
- Let me help you.
- I'll take him back.

365
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:43,600
Jimmy, get the adagio team. Hurry up!

366
00:30:47,700 --> 00:30:49,100
I'll murder you!

367
00:30:49,100 --> 00:30:52,100
Give me that key to Baron's room.
He could get thrown out.

368
00:30:51,900 --> 00:30:53,600
But the way I sang that finish.

369
00:30:53,700 --> 00:30:56,800
Give me that key.
We gotta get Tom on his feet.

370
00:31:01,100 --> 00:31:03,700
Get that make up off and you get yours on.

371
00:31:03,600 --> 00:31:06,200
The stage manager
will be here to see if you died.

372
00:31:06,100 --> 00:31:08,600
- I gotta go on!
- Get this through your head.

373
00:31:08,500 --> 00:31:10,600
You've been on. You just came off.

374
00:31:10,500 --> 00:31:13,100
- You got sick and quit after the first song.
- I did?

375
00:31:13,100 --> 00:31:14,400
Don't you understand?

376
00:31:14,500 --> 00:31:16,900
You weren't on at all. You couldn't make it.

377
00:31:16,900 --> 00:31:20,500
- That idiot went on and sang for you.
- You were a big hit, Tom.

378
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:23,400
I'll talk to you later. Get that makeup off.

379
00:31:26,900 --> 00:31:29,900
He's all right, Jonesy.
Nothing to worry about.

380
00:31:29,800 --> 00:31:33,200
Mr. Hammerstein and Mr. Dockstader
are here to see him.

381
00:31:33,700 --> 00:31:35,600
Hammerstein? Dockstader?

382
00:31:36,900 --> 00:31:39,900
- What's the matter? Let me in!
- Just a minute!

383
00:31:41,300 --> 00:31:43,800
Are you all right?
Did you hear what I told you?

384
00:31:43,700 --> 00:31:46,300
- See, you were a big hit.
- Keep still.

385
00:31:48,900 --> 00:31:50,200
Come in, gentlemen.

386
00:31:50,300 --> 00:31:52,700
He's feeling much better.
Just a little indigestion.

387
00:31:52,700 --> 00:31:55,200
Mr. Baron, gentlemen.
Mr. Dockstader, Mr. Hammerstein.

388
00:31:55,100 --> 00:31:58,000
I'm glad to know you.
You were great out there tonight.

389
00:31:57,900 --> 00:32:00,900
- Sorry you couldn't do more.
- Thank you, Mr. Hammerstein.

390
00:32:00,900 --> 00:32:02,600
This is Steve Martin, gentlemen.

391
00:32:02,600 --> 00:32:05,000
How are you? My partner, Al Jolson.

392
00:32:04,900 --> 00:32:07,000
- How do you do?
- Martin and Jolson.

393
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:10,800
I have an idea you might do very well
at Hammerstein's Victoria...

394
00:32:10,700 --> 00:32:13,800
if you'd consider opening in two weeks?

395
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:17,400
I don't know, Mr. Hammerstein.

396
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:21,100
That's wonderful. He gets an offer
to play on Broadway and he doesn't know.

397
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:22,600
That's a great break.

398
00:32:22,700 --> 00:32:26,200
I don't carry a contract around with me,
but anything will do.

399
00:32:26,100 --> 00:32:28,400
- I'd like to talk to you.
- Who me?

400
00:32:28,400 --> 00:32:29,400
Outside.

401
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:32,600
I'm certain we won't have any trouble
about the terms.

402
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,900
Yes, sir, you're going to enjoy
playing my theater.

403
00:32:36,900 --> 00:32:38,900
What did you say your name was?

404
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:40,400
Al Jolson.

405
00:32:40,500 --> 00:32:44,200
- Did you ever sing in blackface?
- Him? Never.

406
00:32:44,100 --> 00:32:46,700
You see, he just whistles, Mr. Dockstader.

407
00:32:46,600 --> 00:32:49,400
Blacks up behind the ears to whistle.

408
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:53,900
I've seen Baron work before.

409
00:32:54,200 --> 00:32:55,600
Hammerstein hasn't.

410
00:32:55,700 --> 00:32:58,300
- I'll go and explain to Mr. Hammerstein.
- I wouldn't.

411
00:32:58,300 --> 00:33:00,500
Hammerstein knows what he's doing.

412
00:33:01,100 --> 00:33:02,700
I don't tell tales.

413
00:33:03,100 --> 00:33:04,700
As for you, Jolson...

414
00:33:04,900 --> 00:33:08,200
you can join Dockstader's Minstrels
in St. Louis next week.

415
00:33:08,400 --> 00:33:09,700
You don't mean it.

416
00:33:09,900 --> 00:33:12,100
- You hear that?
- That's from heaven!

417
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:13,900
St. Louis next week.

418
00:33:14,400 --> 00:33:17,600
We'd have to leave the show on Saturday.
We can fix that, can't we?

419
00:33:17,500 --> 00:33:20,800
Sure. There's a lot of new stuff
we're planning to put in the act.

420
00:33:20,800 --> 00:33:23,500
- We'll have it ready Saturday.
- I can't use an act.

421
00:33:23,500 --> 00:33:25,600
I only have a place for one man.

422
00:33:26,100 --> 00:33:28,000
You mean you just want me?

423
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:32,200
What did you think?
What would I be doing with minstrels?

424
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:37,200
Steve and I have been together a long time
and we're working up a lot of new ideas.

425
00:33:37,100 --> 00:33:40,500
Not me. You.
But this is what a guy like you prays for.

426
00:33:40,600 --> 00:33:44,500
- Dockstader's Minstrels in one jump.
- Where you can sing your head off.

427
00:33:44,900 --> 00:33:47,100
You mean the job calls for a singer?

428
00:33:47,100 --> 00:33:49,500
What are you talking about?
What did you think?

429
00:33:49,500 --> 00:33:52,900
Then I wouldn't be interested.
See, I like whistling.

430
00:33:52,700 --> 00:33:55,900
Steve and I argue about that all the time.
He wants me to sing...

431
00:33:55,800 --> 00:33:58,300
but at heart I'm a whistler.
It makes me happy.

432
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:00,700
- Martin and Jolson, five minutes.
- That's us.

433
00:34:00,700 --> 00:34:03,800
Thanks a lot.
If you need a whistler, let me know.

434
00:34:03,800 --> 00:34:05,700
Be with you in a minute, Steve.

435
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:11,300
When are you leaving town, Mr. Dockstader?

436
00:34:11,400 --> 00:34:12,800
Tomorrow evening.

437
00:34:13,400 --> 00:34:16,300
I might drop around to your hotel
in the morning.

438
00:34:25,400 --> 00:34:28,500
I wonder what the porter did
with my bags. They're not here.

439
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:31,000
- Must be on the train somewhere.
- I'll see.

440
00:34:45,900 --> 00:34:47,400
Hello, Jolson.

441
00:34:48,100 --> 00:34:51,600
Hello, Mr. Dockstader.
I thought you were going to St. Louis.

442
00:34:51,500 --> 00:34:53,600
I am. So are you.

443
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:56,700
- All aboard!
- Where's Steve?

444
00:34:57,200 --> 00:34:58,700
He's not coming.

445
00:34:58,900 --> 00:35:02,800
- Then I'm on the wrong train.
- No, you're not! This is the right train.

446
00:35:02,700 --> 00:35:04,300
Steve wants you to go with me.

447
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:08,400
- I can't do it, Mr. Dockstader.
- But you're throwing away a great chance.

448
00:35:25,300 --> 00:35:29,300
<i>I want a girl</i>
<i>Just like the girl</i>

449
00:35:29,200 --> 00:35:32,600
<i>That married dear old Dad</i>

450
00:35:32,900 --> 00:35:35,000
<i>She was a pearl</i>

451
00:35:34,900 --> 00:35:39,800
<i>And the only girl</i>
<i>That Daddy ever had</i>

452
00:35:40,100 --> 00:35:44,300
<i>A good old-fashioned girl with heart so true</i>

453
00:35:44,300 --> 00:35:47,700
<i>One who loves nobody else but you</i>

454
00:35:47,600 --> 00:35:51,800
<i>And that's why I want a girl</i>
<i>Just like the girl</i>

455
00:35:51,800 --> 00:35:55,600
<i>That married dear old Dad</i>

456
00:35:56,200 --> 00:35:58,300
Excuse me, Mr. Dockstader.

457
00:35:58,300 --> 00:36:01,200
- It's been almost a year now...
- And you're doing fine.

458
00:36:01,200 --> 00:36:04,000
You're making real progress
and I have some ideas for you.

459
00:36:03,900 --> 00:36:06,200
I'm going to move you into a quartet.

460
00:36:06,200 --> 00:36:10,200
Thanks a lot, Mr. Dockstader,
but you see, I had some ideas myself...

461
00:36:10,200 --> 00:36:12,800
Steve Martin said
you break out with a rash now and then.

462
00:36:12,700 --> 00:36:14,100
Ideas about what?

463
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:17,900
I wanted to talk to you
about the kind of song we're singing.

464
00:36:17,800 --> 00:36:21,000
- Same one always in the same way...
- That's what they come to hear.

465
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:23,700
- It's tradition.
- But they might like something different.

466
00:36:23,700 --> 00:36:27,000
My boy, minstrels have been doing fine
for 50 years.

467
00:36:26,900 --> 00:36:29,600
We take pride in doing it
like it's always been done.

468
00:36:29,400 --> 00:36:31,800
- I know that...
- But you've got a great point there.

469
00:36:31,700 --> 00:36:33,500
We'll talk it over sometime.

470
00:36:34,100 --> 00:36:37,900
<i>She was a pearl and the only girl</i>

471
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:41,500
<i>That Daddy ever had</i>

472
00:36:41,500 --> 00:36:45,400
<i>A good old-fashioned girl with heart so true</i>

473
00:36:45,400 --> 00:36:48,500
<i>One who loves nobody else but you</i>

474
00:36:51,900 --> 00:36:53,700
Excuse me, Mr. Dockstader.

475
00:36:54,300 --> 00:36:57,200
- I've been looking for a chance for weeks...
- I agree.

476
00:36:57,200 --> 00:37:00,000
You've worked in that quartet long enough.
Time you moved up.

477
00:36:59,900 --> 00:37:04,100
- I'm going to give you a chance in a duet.
- That'd be fine, Mr. Dockstader...

478
00:37:04,100 --> 00:37:07,300
but the point is, if I do,
I'd like to try a different kind of song.

479
00:37:07,200 --> 00:37:09,800
I mean something with a style
that's better for me...

480
00:37:09,700 --> 00:37:13,400
faster tempo, more rhythm.
I'd like to look for something like that.

481
00:37:13,400 --> 00:37:15,500
Sure. Talk to you about that again.

482
00:37:15,500 --> 00:37:18,100
Must be some song around
you'd be happy with.

483
00:37:18,800 --> 00:37:22,900
<i>I want a girl, just like the girl</i>

484
00:37:22,900 --> 00:37:26,700
<i>That married dear old Dad</i>

485
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:30,700
<i>She was a pearl and the only girl</i>

486
00:37:30,600 --> 00:37:34,200
<i>That Daddy ever had</i>

487
00:37:35,900 --> 00:37:39,200
- Where you going to eat?
- I think I'll take a look at the town.

488
00:37:39,200 --> 00:37:43,600
- I've never been in New Orleans before.
- Don't get lost. We've got a show tonight.

489
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:21,300
Mr. Dockstader,
Jolson hasn't showed up yet.

490
00:38:21,300 --> 00:38:23,700
It's too late now anyway. Cut the duet.

491
00:38:58,100 --> 00:39:00,300
I'm sorry I'm late...

492
00:39:00,300 --> 00:39:02,800
It's intermission.
We had to skip your number.

493
00:39:04,200 --> 00:39:06,000
I'm very sorry.

494
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:07,300
I just forgot.

495
00:39:07,300 --> 00:39:10,700
I know that sounds crazy,
but I heard some music tonight...

496
00:39:10,700 --> 00:39:12,400
something they call "jazz."

497
00:39:12,400 --> 00:39:15,900
Some fellas just make it up
as they go along. They pick it out of the air.

498
00:39:15,900 --> 00:39:18,500
They tell me they play it
for weddings, funerals...

499
00:39:18,400 --> 00:39:19,700
Funerals?

500
00:39:19,800 --> 00:39:22,800
Don't get the wrong idea.
You've never heard anything like this.

501
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:26,600
I sang with them. Nothing with words,
because the song doesn't have any.

502
00:39:26,400 --> 00:39:28,300
In fact, it isn't even a song.

503
00:39:28,300 --> 00:39:30,200
But you can make it one
and get words to fit.

504
00:39:30,200 --> 00:39:31,900
It just needs to be worked on a little.

505
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:35,000
It's exciting.
It'll make the show a hundred times better.

506
00:39:34,900 --> 00:39:38,600
I'm happy with the show as it is.
But you aren't, are you?

507
00:39:39,300 --> 00:39:41,000
In fact, you never will be.

508
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:43,300
You'll always be chasing something
up ahead...

509
00:39:43,300 --> 00:39:47,100
and keep forgetting your act
in a little thing like a minstrel show.

510
00:39:47,800 --> 00:39:50,100
So, maybe, we ought to call it quits.

511
00:39:52,100 --> 00:39:53,500
Don't you think so?

512
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:56,800
Yeah, I think you're right.

513
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:01,400
Good luck, Jolson.
I hope you find what you are looking for.

514
00:40:02,200 --> 00:40:03,800
Thanks, Mr. Dockstader.

515
00:40:12,500 --> 00:40:15,200
Papa, you're not
going to start again tonight?

516
00:40:15,400 --> 00:40:17,600
Can't a man ask himself questions?

517
00:40:17,900 --> 00:40:20,200
In six months, three cards.

518
00:40:20,400 --> 00:40:22,100
I would really like to understand.

519
00:40:22,100 --> 00:40:25,500
He leaves Dockstader
and then no cards. Why?

520
00:40:25,700 --> 00:40:28,600
Because he did not leave Dockstader
for a better position...

521
00:40:28,500 --> 00:40:31,100
because, for a long time, he isn't working.

522
00:40:37,700 --> 00:40:41,600
Excuse me, are you the Yoelsons
who have a talented son in show business?

523
00:40:45,600 --> 00:40:47,600
Yup, it's the right Yoelsons.

524
00:40:47,700 --> 00:40:49,300
Mama, you got younger.

525
00:40:49,500 --> 00:40:52,200
- Why didn't you say you were coming?
- Isn't this better?

526
00:40:52,100 --> 00:40:54,900
- This way Mama's having a good cry.
- How are you?

527
00:40:54,900 --> 00:40:57,400
- Look at him, a man.
- Did you eat, Asa?

528
00:40:57,300 --> 00:41:00,400
- Eat? What's that?
- Mama, he didn't eat!

529
00:41:00,300 --> 00:41:05,200
Come on, sit down. Papa and I just finished,
but there's plenty. I got everything.

530
00:41:05,700 --> 00:41:09,100
I got to tell Ann!
Sit down. Make him sit down, Papa.

531
00:41:08,900 --> 00:41:10,300
Ann Murray!

532
00:41:12,200 --> 00:41:13,900
Why is she so excited?

533
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:16,500
What's there to be so excited about?

534
00:41:18,600 --> 00:41:22,300
Mama takes all the medals.
Still the best cook in the United States.

535
00:41:22,200 --> 00:41:25,400
After what you've been eating,
by comparison I'm wonderful.

536
00:41:25,300 --> 00:41:29,500
Look at him. Shows you what you can tell
from pictures. He is skin and bones.

537
00:41:31,100 --> 00:41:32,400
You see...

538
00:41:34,100 --> 00:41:36,700
That's nice, to put a cap on when you eat.

539
00:41:36,700 --> 00:41:37,800
But, Asa...

540
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:40,600
did you wear one all the time
you were away?

541
00:41:40,600 --> 00:41:43,900
- As a matter of fact, I didn't.
- For me, it's not necessary.

542
00:41:45,100 --> 00:41:49,600
- Gefilte fish I made this morning.
- And horseradish, fresh-grated an hour ago.

543
00:41:49,500 --> 00:41:51,900
Look out for it, Asa. It's very strong.

544
00:41:52,500 --> 00:41:54,900
Who's that again? Not Ann Murray?

545
00:41:55,200 --> 00:41:57,700
Of course. She grew up.
And look how pretty.

546
00:41:57,700 --> 00:41:59,100
That's what I mean. It can't be.

547
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:02,000
She was just a funny little girl
with funny ribbons in her hair.

548
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:05,400
Listen to that, Mama.
And you were such a prize, I suppose?

549
00:42:05,300 --> 00:42:07,400
- Asa was a beautiful boy.
- You see?

550
00:42:07,400 --> 00:42:10,300
- Let him eat. The fish.
- I can taste this already.

551
00:42:10,200 --> 00:42:13,400
- Not too much horseradish.
- I don't have to worry about...

552
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:17,400
Magnificent.

553
00:42:17,400 --> 00:42:19,400
See? I knew he would like it.

554
00:42:22,700 --> 00:42:24,300
Wonderful, Mama.

555
00:42:24,300 --> 00:42:28,100
Really, the best you ever made.
Mama, you're terrific.

556
00:42:28,600 --> 00:42:32,100
- Tell me, Papa, how's everybody been?
- Mama and I have been well.

557
00:42:32,100 --> 00:42:35,800
By the way, do you know who came
to see us a few weeks ago? Steve Martin.

558
00:42:35,700 --> 00:42:37,400
- How is he?
- I don't know.

559
00:42:37,400 --> 00:42:38,800
He didn't look so well.

560
00:42:38,800 --> 00:42:41,500
He said he was picking up time.

561
00:42:41,500 --> 00:42:44,200
- Is that good?
- Lf you don't have a regular booking...

562
00:42:44,200 --> 00:42:47,100
that means you're picking up
whatever work you can get.

563
00:42:46,900 --> 00:42:49,600
- And you...
- Papa, please, he's eating.

564
00:42:49,600 --> 00:42:51,400
- You can talk business later.
- I'm sorry.

565
00:42:51,400 --> 00:42:52,900
It's all right, Mama.

566
00:42:52,900 --> 00:42:55,700
It's true. I've been picking up a little time
now and then.

567
00:42:55,600 --> 00:42:57,100
- You see...
- But wait.

568
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:00,800
I'd have had regular booking
if I'd wanted it. But I've had other ideas.

569
00:43:00,700 --> 00:43:03,200
They sound a little crazy to anyone but me.

570
00:43:03,200 --> 00:43:04,500
Like what, Asa?

571
00:43:05,200 --> 00:43:08,700
Like spending most of my time
in hotel rooms with songwriters...

572
00:43:08,600 --> 00:43:10,500
whenever I met up with one...

573
00:43:10,800 --> 00:43:13,200
trying to make songs out of music
I picked up.

574
00:43:13,200 --> 00:43:17,000
Music nobody ever heard of before,
but the only kind I want to sing.

575
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:18,800
Is this music so peculiar?

576
00:43:20,200 --> 00:43:22,200
You sing it all the time, Papa.

577
00:43:22,100 --> 00:43:26,300
- You want to sing prayers on the stage?
- No, just the feeling in prayers.

578
00:43:26,500 --> 00:43:28,400
That's what's in the people I got it from...

579
00:43:28,400 --> 00:43:32,000
and that's what's in their music,
even when it's fast and happy.

580
00:43:32,200 --> 00:43:34,300
But they tell me it won't go, Papa.

581
00:43:34,300 --> 00:43:37,300
It's never been done.
In fact, I'll tell you a secret.

582
00:43:37,600 --> 00:43:39,800
They say your son's a little crazy.

583
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:42,800
Mama, our son is a little crazy.

584
00:43:42,900 --> 00:43:46,300
But what can we do? He is our boy.
We have got to love him.

585
00:43:46,400 --> 00:43:48,400
But about crazy people, Asa...

586
00:43:49,200 --> 00:43:50,500
it's very funny.

587
00:43:50,500 --> 00:43:54,600
See, once they prove they are right,
they are suddenly great people.

588
00:43:56,900 --> 00:43:58,600
I'll go. Eat, Asa.

589
00:44:05,500 --> 00:44:07,200
Hello. Yes?

590
00:44:08,200 --> 00:44:09,300
New York?

591
00:44:09,600 --> 00:44:11,100
Hello. Yes?

592
00:44:11,700 --> 00:44:12,700
Who?

593
00:44:13,300 --> 00:44:14,300
Al?

594
00:44:16,400 --> 00:44:19,800
Asa? He is right here.
Yes, and who is this, please?

595
00:44:20,100 --> 00:44:21,200
Baron?

596
00:44:23,200 --> 00:44:25,100
A Mr. Tom Baron.

597
00:44:25,400 --> 00:44:28,000
Hello, Tom? How are you?

598
00:44:28,200 --> 00:44:30,300
Where'd you drop from?
How'd you know I was here?

599
00:44:30,300 --> 00:44:34,000
I got your home address from an agency.
It's about this, Al.

600
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:36,500
You remember that contract
with Hammerstein?

601
00:44:37,200 --> 00:44:41,300
I was so bad that he paid me off
if I'd stop singing.

602
00:44:41,600 --> 00:44:45,400
That's how it happens I'm managing
the new Winter Garden Theatre.

603
00:44:45,500 --> 00:44:47,900
I got you to thank for the whole thing.

604
00:44:48,200 --> 00:44:51,100
Look, my friend, we open in three weeks.

605
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:53,900
There's a spot in the show for you,
if you want it.

606
00:44:53,700 --> 00:44:55,200
If I want it?

607
00:44:56,100 --> 00:44:57,400
Winter Garden?

608
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:02,600
Yes, I heard you, Tom. It's just a spot...

609
00:45:04,500 --> 00:45:05,700
but Broadway.

610
00:45:05,700 --> 00:45:07,300
Except, tell me, Tom, what do I do?

611
00:45:07,400 --> 00:45:10,500
- I mean, exactly what do I sing?
- I don't know.

612
00:45:10,300 --> 00:45:12,900
Any one of the songs
that's been written for the show.

613
00:45:12,900 --> 00:45:14,800
Why can't I pick my own, Tom?

614
00:45:15,200 --> 00:45:18,300
Not exactly my own.
It's stuff I picked up. Terrific songs.

615
00:45:18,300 --> 00:45:21,500
They need to be polished up
by someone good. Won't take much time.

616
00:45:21,500 --> 00:45:23,900
They're terrific, but not written yet?

617
00:45:23,800 --> 00:45:27,100
What's the good, if it won't help the show
and I can't do what I can?

618
00:45:26,900 --> 00:45:29,700
I don't care if it's the biggest show,
I rather pass it up.

619
00:45:29,700 --> 00:45:32,800
Let me bring the stuff on
and help me get it into shape.

620
00:45:33,700 --> 00:45:36,600
You will? You're marvelous.

621
00:45:37,700 --> 00:45:40,500
I can leave right away.
I'll be on that train in an hour.

622
00:45:40,500 --> 00:45:43,900
- He just came home.
- Right, Tom, the minute I get there.

623
00:45:45,400 --> 00:45:49,200
- Asa, you are leaving?
- Just right next door, New York. I'll be back.

624
00:45:49,400 --> 00:45:51,600
Honey, what a break this is.

625
00:45:51,600 --> 00:45:54,700
New York, Broadway,
Winter Garden, here I come.

626
00:45:54,600 --> 00:45:57,800
How do you like that?
It's got to be his own song...

627
00:45:57,800 --> 00:46:01,300
- and his own way of singing it.
- Hasn't changed a day.

628
00:46:01,600 --> 00:46:04,600
Thanks a lot.
Don't tell him I had anything to do with it.

629
00:46:04,600 --> 00:46:07,200
This could turn out to be a pack of trouble.

630
00:46:07,300 --> 00:46:10,400
Al? Trouble? I can't imagine what you mean.

631
00:46:27,600 --> 00:46:30,000
Show's running too long.
It's almost 11:00 p.m.

632
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:31,600
- Who's on next?
- Jolson.

633
00:46:31,700 --> 00:46:33,900
- Cut him and jump to the finish.
- Wait a minute.

634
00:46:33,800 --> 00:46:35,800
Tell the orchestra leader about it.

635
00:46:35,700 --> 00:46:38,800
Look, I want to go on.
Where's Baron? Ask Tom.

636
00:46:38,700 --> 00:46:41,200
Baron isn't running this end of it. I am.

637
00:46:41,900 --> 00:46:44,300
- Hold it. You're not on.
- That's what you think.

638
00:46:44,300 --> 00:46:46,000
We're cutting the Jolson number.

639
00:46:46,800 --> 00:46:48,300
I'm next, folks.

640
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:52,400
- You lucky people.
- But he's here, in front of me.

641
00:46:52,400 --> 00:46:56,600
Oscar, what are you doing with that phone?
This is no time to call up women.

642
00:46:57,400 --> 00:47:00,700
- I can't get up there and pull him off.
- Close the curtains on him.

643
00:47:00,500 --> 00:47:03,800
Oscar, if you insist on phoning,
get one for me.

644
00:47:06,100 --> 00:47:08,900
Hello, Oscar, remember me? Jolson.

645
00:47:09,100 --> 00:47:10,900
Now, boys, take it easy.

646
00:47:10,900 --> 00:47:14,500
Next they'll turn out the lights on me,
but I wouldn't mind that.

647
00:47:14,300 --> 00:47:17,200
Professor, my song, if you please.

648
00:47:18,900 --> 00:47:21,900
Settle back, folks.
You ain't heard nothing yet.

649
00:47:25,300 --> 00:47:29,000
<i>Everything seems lovely</i>

650
00:47:28,900 --> 00:47:31,300
<i>when you start to roam</i>

651
00:47:32,600 --> 00:47:36,000
<i>The birds are singing the day that you stray</i>

652
00:47:36,200 --> 00:47:39,000
<i>But wait until you are further away</i>

653
00:47:39,600 --> 00:47:42,700
<i>Things won't be so lovely</i>

654
00:47:43,100 --> 00:47:45,700
<i>When you're all alone</i>

655
00:47:46,500 --> 00:47:51,400
<i>Here's what you'll keep saying</i>

656
00:47:52,500 --> 00:47:55,500
<i>when you're far from home</i>

657
00:47:56,500 --> 00:47:59,200
<i>Mammy</i>

658
00:48:00,200 --> 00:48:02,800
<i>Mammy</i>

659
00:48:03,300 --> 00:48:06,700
<i>The sun shines east, the sun shines west</i>

660
00:48:07,400 --> 00:48:10,300
<i>I know where the sun shines best</i>

661
00:48:11,100 --> 00:48:13,300
<i>Mammy</i>

662
00:48:14,500 --> 00:48:17,400
<i>My little mammy</i>

663
00:48:17,800 --> 00:48:19,500
<i>My heartstrings</i>

664
00:48:19,600 --> 00:48:24,600
<i>are tangled around Alabamy</i>

665
00:48:25,600 --> 00:48:27,700
<i>I'm a-comin'</i>

666
00:48:28,900 --> 00:48:31,800
<i>Sorry that I made you wait</i>

667
00:48:33,100 --> 00:48:35,100
<i>I'm a-comin'</i>

668
00:48:36,100 --> 00:48:38,700
<i>Hope and trust that I'm not late</i>

669
00:48:40,300 --> 00:48:42,300
<i>Mammy</i>

670
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:46,800
<i>My little mammy</i>

671
00:48:46,700 --> 00:48:49,100
<i>I'd walk a million miles</i>

672
00:48:49,100 --> 00:48:51,200
<i>For one of your smiles</i>

673
00:48:51,500 --> 00:48:53,400
<i>My mammy</i>

674
00:48:56,900 --> 00:48:58,300
<i>Mammy</i>

675
00:48:59,900 --> 00:49:01,900
<i>My little mammy</i>

676
00:49:02,100 --> 00:49:05,600
<i>The sun shines east, the sun shines west</i>

677
00:49:06,200 --> 00:49:09,200
<i>I know where the sun shines best</i>

678
00:49:09,900 --> 00:49:12,200
<i>It's on my mammy I'm talking about</i>

679
00:49:12,400 --> 00:49:16,300
<i>Nobody else's, my little mammy</i>

680
00:49:16,800 --> 00:49:20,600
<i>My heartstrings are tangled around</i>

681
00:49:20,900 --> 00:49:24,100
<i>Alabamy</i>

682
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:26,000
<i>Mammy</i>

683
00:49:26,400 --> 00:49:28,200
<i>Mammy, I'm comin'</i>

684
00:49:30,200 --> 00:49:32,100
<i>I hope I didn't make you wait</i>

685
00:49:32,900 --> 00:49:35,800
<i>Mammy, I'm coming</i>

686
00:49:37,700 --> 00:49:39,400
<i>I hope I'm not late</i>

687
00:49:39,800 --> 00:49:42,200
<i>Mammy, look at me</i>

688
00:49:42,600 --> 00:49:46,400
<i>Don't you know me? I'm your little baby</i>

689
00:49:46,400 --> 00:49:51,100
<i>I'd walk a million miles</i>
<i>for one of your smiles</i>

690
00:49:51,200 --> 00:49:56,200
<i>My mammy</i>

691
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:16,700
Asa smashed something?

692
00:50:34,200 --> 00:50:37,200
That actor you wanted to interview
for the new show...

693
00:50:37,200 --> 00:50:39,400
- want to see him now?
- Send him in.

694
00:50:43,400 --> 00:50:46,700
Hello, Steve. Haven't seen you
in a long time. How have you been?

695
00:50:46,800 --> 00:50:48,700
Fine. Glad to see you, Al.

696
00:50:48,900 --> 00:50:50,800
Sit down. Just cleaning up.

697
00:50:57,400 --> 00:50:59,200
Look, about this part, Al.

698
00:50:59,300 --> 00:51:02,200
It's nice of you to think of me,
but it might not be right.

699
00:51:02,100 --> 00:51:05,500
- I'm considering a few other things...
- Sure, I realize that.

700
00:51:05,900 --> 00:51:10,200
But it's like this. I've clicked on Broadway
and things are piling up on me.

701
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:12,700
Music contracts, record-making,
sheet music.

702
00:51:12,700 --> 00:51:15,700
Now we're putting together a new show
starring Al.

703
00:51:15,600 --> 00:51:17,700
It's a great show.
You should hear the songs.

704
00:51:17,700 --> 00:51:21,800
- We go into rehearsal next week.
